rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to record the Asset in an index.
The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to run the computer program Asset.
The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to have a text Asset read out loud to an audience.
The Assigner requires that the Assignee(s) compensates the Assigner (or other specified compensation Party) by some amount of value, if defined, for use of the Asset.
The Assigner requires that the Assignee(s) has(ve) a person review the Policy applicable to the Asset.
The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to display the visual media Asset to an audience or the public.
The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to make (an) exact reproduction(s) of the Asset.

rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Privacy
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment:
Policy expressions that stipulate the terms of usage over personal information.
NOTE:Must contain at least the Party entity with Assigner role and a Party with Assignee role. Must also contain a Duty on the assignee related to obligations towards managing the assigner’s Asset containing personal information. The Assignee is being granted the terms of the Privacy policy from the Assigner.
The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to perform or exhibit an Asset to an audience.
The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to transfer the ownership of the Asset to a third party with compensation and while deleting the original asset.

Policy expressions that propose terms of usage from an Asset owner.
NOTE: Must contain a Party entity with Assigner role. The Offer may contain a Party entity with Assignee role, but does not grant any privileges to that Party. Non contractual state.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Offer

rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: The Assigner requires that the Assignee(s) unload(s) and delete(s) the computer program Asset from a storage device and disable(s) its readiness for operation.
The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee to use the Asset as agreed.
Reasons to deprecate: Despite field mentioned in spec ODRL OWL do not implement this
The Assigner requires that the Assignee(s) attributes the Asset to the Assigner or an attributed Party.

ODRLCHUB= SPECIFY THE SEMANTIC OF PROHITION permit = default_everything_allowed-prohibition+permission prohib = default_nothing_allowed+permission-prohibition invalid = default_nothing_allowed+permission

rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Aggreement
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment:
Policy expressions that are formal contracts (or licenses) stipulating all the terms of usage and all the parties involve.
NOTE:Must contain at least the Party entity with Assigner role and a Party with Assignee role. The latter being granted the terms of the Agreement from the former.
The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to create a new derivative Asset from this Asset and to edit or modify the derivative.

rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Constraint
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment:
Representation of a constraint.
Constraint need to be aligned with metadata
The Assigner requires that the Assignee(s) grants the specified Policy to a third party for their use of the Asset.
The Assigner requires that the Assignee(s) apply(ies) a watermark as provided by the Assigner to the Asset.

rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Policy
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment:
An ODRL policy representing an agreement or a potential agreement.
Policy is the central entity that holds an ODRL policy together. In its encoded form, e.g. in an XML document, it makes the policy addressable from the outside word via its uid attribute. Policy can refer to Permissions and Prohibitions.
The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to anonymize all or parts of the Asset.
The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to transfer the ownership of the Asset to a third party without compensation and while deleting the original asset.
The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to obtain data from the Asset.

The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to update existing content of the Asset. A new asset is not created by this action.
This action will modify an asset which is typically updated from time to time without creating a new asset like a database. If the result from modifying the asset should be a new asset the actions derive or extract should be used. (Note that the notion of whether or not the change is significant enough to qualify as a new asset is subjective.)

Policy expressions that consists of entities from the complete model
NOTE:The Set is aimed at scenarios where there is an open criteria for the semantics of the policy expressions and typically refined by other systems/profiles that process the information at a later time. No privileges are granted to any Party.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Set
Party
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: A party represent a legal person having duties and rights as part of agreements.
The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to translate the original natural language of an Asset into another natural language.
The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to create multiple copies of the Asset that are being concurrently used.
The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to use the Asset or parts of it as part of a composite collection.
Reasons to deprecate: dataType should be specified by schema - additional OWL SPEC of ODRL is wrong here
The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to make a digital copy of the digital Asset in another digital format.
The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to load the computer program Asset onto a storage device which allows operating or running the Asset.

rdf:Description.ns5:description:
Open Digital Right Language 2.1
This is a digital catapult copyright hub alternative implementation of ODRL.
Differences with W3C version: Attempt to include and follow the different version of the specfication. (ODRL 2.1 SPEC, ODRL OWL , ODRL JSON). Some elements are not described in same ways in different versions (conflict terms, reference to "types", "names", "ids"... ) Some elements have been added for compatibility with json-odrl encoding.
Some elements that we estimate not specified enough to be useful are considered for removal.

rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to print an Asset onto paper or to create a hard copy.

The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee to grant the use the Asset to third parties.
This action enables the Assignee to create policies for the use of the Asset for third parties. nextPolicy is recommended to be agreed with the third party. Use of temporal constraints is recommended.
The Assigner requires that the Assignee(s) permanently removes all copies of the Asset.

An asset represent any object a policy can apply to.
The Asset entity is aimed at identifying the content that is the subject of an ODRL policy, e.g. a media file or ebook. Furthermore, it can be used to represent other Asset entities that are needed to undertake the Policy expression, such as with the Duty entity. The Asset entity is referred to by the Permission and/or Prohibition entities, and also by the Duty entity.
The Asset entity contains the following attribute:
uid: the unique identification of the Asset (REQUIRED) The identification of the Asset entity is a key foundation of the ODRL Policy language. However, there are some use cases where the ODRL Policy expression MAY be embedded inside the target Asset. In these cases, it MAY be more appropriate to provide, or infer, a link to the Asset entity (as the complete Asset uid may not be known at the time) through the local context. Use of such inference and context MUST be documented in the relevant ODRL community Profile.
Since ODRL policies could deal with any kind of asset, the ODRL Core Model does not provide additional metadata to describe Asset entities of particular media types. It is recommended to use already existing metadata standards, such as Dublin Core Metadata Terms that are appropriate to the Asset type or purpose.
The Relation entity is used to associate the Asset entity with the relevant Permission, Prohibition, and Duty entities
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Asset

rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: The Assigner requires that the Assignee(s) include(s) other related assets in the Asset.
The Assigner requires that the Assignee(s) accepts that the use of the Asset may be tracked

rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Rule
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment:
Permission, Prohibition and Duty are Rules.
In order for "function" to complete "action" and to obtain "relation", function must satisfay constaint ?
The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to store the Asset (in a non-transient form).

A Permission allows a particular Action to be executed on a related Asset, e.g. “play the audio file abc.mp3”. A Constraint like “at most 10 times” might be added to specify the Permission more precisely. The Party that grants this Permission is linked to it with the Role assigner, the Party that is granted the Permission is linked to it with the Role assignee, e.g. “assigner VirtualMusicShop grants the Permission to assignee Alice”. Additionally, a Permission MAY be linked to Duty entities.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Permission

rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to add explanatory notations/commentaries to the Asset without modifying the Asset in any other way.
The Assignee requires that the Assigner(s) ensure(s) that the permission on the Asset is exclusive to the Assignee.
The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to create a new derivative Asset from this Asset and to edit or modify the derivative.

rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Ticket
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment:
Policy expressions that stipulate the terms of usage and is redeemable by any Party who currently holds the Ticket in their possession.
NOTE:May contain the Party entity with Assigner role and the Party entity with Assignee role. A Ticket (or Voucher) may be anonymous or personalised, where the holder of that Ticket may remain unknown or has to be identified. The holder, or if known, the Assignee, is being granted the terms of the Ticket from the Assigner (in known).

The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to move the Asset from one digital location to another including deleting the original copy.
After the Asset has been moved, the original copy must be deleted.
The Assigner requires that the Assignee(s) obtains explicit consent from the Assigner or a consenting Party to perform the requested action in relation to the Asset.

Policy expressions that propose terms of usage to an Asset owner
Must contain a Party entity with Assignee role. The Request may also contain the Party entity with Assigner role if this is known. No privileges are granted to any Party.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Request
Prohibition
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: The Prohibition entity is used in the same way as Permission, with the two differences that it does not refer to Duties and (obviously) that it forbids the Action, e.g. “Alice is forbidden to use abc.mp3 commercially”.

The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to extract parts of the Asset and to use it as a new Asset.
A new asset is created and may have very little in common with the original Asset. (Note that the notion of whether or not the change is significant enough to qualify as a new asset is subjective.) To the extracted Asset a next policy may be applied.
The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to perform an audio Asset to an audience.

rdf:Description.rdfs:label: Duty
rdf:Description.rdfs:comment: Similar to Permissions, a Duty states that a certain Action MAY be executed by the Party with the Role assignee for the Permission to be valid, e.g. “Alice must pay 5 EUR in order to get the Permission to play abc.mp3″.
The Assigner requires that the Assignee(s) inform(s) the Assigner or an informed Party that an action has been performed on or in relation to the Asset.
The Assigner permits/prohibits the Assignee(s) to distribute the Asset.
